{{Infobox venue | name = The National Gugak Center | nickname = | image = [[File:National Gugak Center in Seocho-gu, Seoul, South Korea.jpg|250px|alt=The National Gugak Center]] | image_caption = The National Gugak Center | address = | location = [[Seocho-dong|Seocho-dong, Seocho-gu, Seoul, South Korea]] | coordinates = {{coords|37|28|39.50|N|127|0|3|E}} | type = [[Performing arts center]] | genre = [[Traditional Korean music]] (''gugak'') | built = | opened = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | renovated = | expanded = | closed = | demolished = | owner = | construction_cost = | former_names = The National Center for Korean Traditional Performing Arts | seating_type = | seating_capacity = | website = {{URL|gugak.go.kr}} }}
{{Infobox Korean name | title = Korean name | hangul = {{linktext|국|립|국|악|원}} | hanja = {{linktext|國|立|國|樂|院}} | rr = Gungnip Gukagwon | mr = Kungnip Kugagwŏn}}
The '''National Gugak Center''', located in [[Seoul]], [[South Korea]], is the primary institution of learning for Korean traditional music.
With a history dating back to the {{Interlanguage link multi|Eumseongseo|ko|3=음성서}} music institute of the [[Silla]] kingdom in the 7th century, The National Center for Korean Traditional Performing Arts was founded under its present name in 1950.
It is dedicated to "preserving and promoting traditional Korean music."<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20170302033024/http://www.gugak.go.kr/eng/min/introduction.htm] </ref> Through academic courses, private study, ensembles, research, and performances, it preserves Korea's ancient musical traditions, including the ancient court ritual music called ''[[aak]]'' as well as the ritual music performed for the [[Jongmyo]] (royal ancestral shrine) and the [[Munmyo]] ([[Korean Confucianism|Confucian]] shrine).
